// 1. React Rendering & Re-rendering
React re-renders a component when its state, props, or context changes. However, re-render does not mean DOM update. React uses Virtual DOM and reconciliation to compare previous and next UI, and only updates the changed parts. Parent re-render triggers child re-render unless optimized. Understanding this helps avoid unnecessary renders using memoization. Key optimization tools include React.memo, useMemo, and useCallback. Senior engineers focus on minimizing expensive renders rather than avoiding all renders.

// 2. Virtual DOM
Virtual DOM is a lightweight JavaScript representation of the real DOM. React updates this virtual tree first, compares it with the previous version (diffing), and then applies minimal changes to the real DOM. This improves performance by avoiding direct DOM manipulation. However, Virtual DOM is not always faster—it depends on how efficiently updates are handled. The main advantage is predictable UI updates and abstraction over manual DOM handling.

// 3. Reconciliation Algorithm
Reconciliation is React’s process of comparing two Virtual DOM trees to determine what changed. It uses heuristics like element type and keys to optimize diffing. If element types differ, React destroys and rebuilds nodes. Keys help React identify list items efficiently. Poor key usage (like index) can cause incorrect UI updates and performance issues. Understanding reconciliation is critical for optimizing list rendering and dynamic UI updates.

// 4. React Fiber
React Fiber is the reimplementation of React’s core algorithm enabling incremental rendering. It allows React to pause, resume, and prioritize work. This is important for handling large UI updates without blocking the main thread. Fiber introduces concepts like priority levels and scheduling. It powers features like concurrent rendering. Senior engineers should understand Fiber to debug performance issues and understand how React schedules updates.

// 5. useState Hook
useState is used to manage local component state. It returns a state value and a setter function. Updates are asynchronous and may be batched. Using functional updates (prev => prev + 1) ensures correct state when multiple updates occur. Avoid storing derived state unnecessarily. useState should be used for simple local state, while complex logic may require useReducer.

// 6. useEffect Hook
useEffect handles side effects like API calls, subscriptions, and DOM updates. It runs after render. Dependency array controls when it runs. Missing dependencies can cause stale data, while incorrect dependencies can cause infinite loops. Cleanup function prevents memory leaks. Senior engineers must handle edge cases like race conditions and proper cleanup.

// 7. useMemo
useMemo memoizes expensive calculations to avoid recomputation. It recalculates only when dependencies change. Overuse can harm performance due to memory overhead. Use it for expensive operations like filtering large lists. It helps maintain stable references when passing props to memoized components.

// 8. useCallback
useCallback memoizes functions to prevent unnecessary re-renders when passing callbacks to child components. It is useful when used with React.memo. However, it should not be overused as it adds complexity. It ensures stable function references across renders.

// 9. React.memo
React.memo prevents re-rendering of functional components if props haven’t changed. It uses shallow comparison. It is useful for optimizing pure components. However, if props are objects/functions recreated each render, memo won’t work effectively.

// 10. useRef
useRef provides a mutable reference that persists across renders without causing re-renders. It is used for accessing DOM elements and storing mutable values. Unlike state, updating ref does not trigger re-render. Useful for timers, previous values, and DOM manipulation.

// 11. Controlled vs Uncontrolled Components
Controlled components use React state to manage form inputs, while uncontrolled components use DOM refs. Controlled components provide better control and validation, while uncontrolled components are simpler and more performant for basic use cases.

// 12. Keys in React
Keys help React identify list elements during reconciliation. Stable and unique keys improve performance and prevent UI bugs. Using index as key can cause issues when list order changes.

// 13. Lifting State Up
Lifting state up means moving shared state to the nearest common ancestor. This ensures consistency across components. It avoids duplication but may increase prop drilling.

// 14. Context API
Context provides a way to share state globally without prop drilling. It is useful for themes, auth, and global settings. However, excessive use can cause performance issues due to re-renders.

// 15. Prop Drilling
Prop drilling occurs when props are passed through multiple layers unnecessarily. It can make code hard to maintain. Solutions include Context API or state management libraries.

// 16. Error Boundaries
Error boundaries catch JavaScript errors in component trees and display fallback UI. They improve app stability. Only class components can be error boundaries.

// 17. Code Splitting
Code splitting reduces bundle size by loading code on demand. React.lazy and Suspense are used for this. It improves initial load performance.

// 18. Lazy Loading
Lazy loading delays loading of components until needed. Useful for routes and large components. It improves performance and user experience.

// 19. Portals
Portals allow rendering components outside the DOM hierarchy. Useful for modals, tooltips, and overlays.

// 20. Fragments
Fragments allow grouping elements without adding extra DOM nodes. Helps keep DOM clean and improves performance.


// 21. Concurrent Rendering
Concurrent rendering allows React to interrupt and prioritize updates. It improves UI responsiveness by splitting rendering work into chunks. It is powered by React Fiber. Features like useTransition and useDeferredValue help manage priority updates.

// 22. useTransition
useTransition allows marking updates as non-urgent. It keeps UI responsive during heavy rendering. Useful for filtering large lists or navigation.

// 23. useDeferredValue
Defers a value update to avoid blocking UI. Useful when typing into input while rendering heavy components.

// 24. Batching Updates
React batches multiple state updates into a single render for performance. In React 18, batching works even in async operations.

// 25. Synthetic Events
React wraps browser events into a consistent API. This improves cross-browser compatibility and performance.

// 26. Event Delegation
React attaches event listeners at root instead of individual nodes. This reduces memory usage and improves performance.

// 27. Strict Mode
Helps identify unsafe lifecycle usage and side effects. It intentionally double-invokes some functions in development.

// 28. Hydration
Hydration attaches event listeners to server-rendered HTML. Mismatch between server and client causes issues.

// 29. SSR (Server Side Rendering)
Server renders HTML before sending to client. Improves SEO and initial load performance.

// 30. CSR (Client Side Rendering)
Rendering happens in browser after JS loads. Suitable for highly interactive apps.

// 31. SSG (Static Site Generation)
Pages are generated at build time. Fast and SEO-friendly. Used in static content.

// 32. Incremental Static Regeneration
Allows updating static pages after deployment. Combines benefits of SSR and SSG.

// 33. Routing in React
